  "opinion": "As a 61-year-old electrician in Chicago with a background in hands-on work and a modest education, I've seen the world change in ways that often make me reflect on how we approach problems like the gender gap in science. The gender gap isn't just about numbers—it's about the stories we tell ourselves. Back in my day, when I was a young man, science was seen as a field for boys, and that attitude still lingers in subtle ways today. I've heard from many women in my community who feel they're not quite 'cut out' for the kind of technical work I do, even though they have the skills. It's not about gender per se, but about the cultural messages we send—like how we value certain types of problem-solving over others. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big, sweeping policies that ignore the real-life context of people's lives. For example, in my neighborhood, many women are working multiple jobs to support their families, and science education programs that assume everyone has the same time and resources aren't helping. What works better is creating opportunities that fit into people's existing schedules—like after-school clubs or online courses that don't require a full-time commitment. My Buddhist beliefs teach me to focus on compassion and understanding, so I believe the key is listening more than lecturing. We need to ask: What does a woman in Chicago need to succeed in science, and how can we make it possible without overwhelming her? The answer isn't one-size-fits-all. It's about adapting to the real world, not trying to fit the world to a theory.",
